# 3-Bit Flash ADC using TIQ Comparator (90nm CMOS)

## Overview
This project presents the design and implementation of a 3-bit Flash Analog-to-Digital Converter (ADC) using Threshold Inverter Quantization (TIQ) comparators in 90nm CMOS technology. The design focuses on achieving low power consumption, high speed, and reduced circuit complexity.

The system was designed and simulated using Cadence Virtuoso.

---

## Features
- 3-bit Flash ADC design
- Uses TIQ comparators instead of traditional comparators
- Eliminates resistor ladder network
- Low power consumption: 300 µW
- High speed operation: 40 µs delay
- Implemented using 90nm CMOS technology
- Designed using Cadence Virtuoso

---

## Working Principle

The Flash ADC consists of:

### 1. TIQ Comparators
- Total comparators: 7
- Each comparator has different threshold voltage
- Threshold range: 0.2V to 0.8V
- Implemented using CMOS inverter

Each comparator produces:
- Logic 1 → if Vin > Threshold
- Logic 0 → if Vin < Threshold

This generates a thermometer code.

### 2. Priority Encoder
The priority encoder converts thermometer code into binary output.

Example:

Thermometer code: 1110000  
Binary output: 100

---

## Block Diagram

Analog Input → TIQ Comparators → Priority Encoder → Digital Output

---

## Tools Used

- Cadence Virtuoso
- 90nm CMOS Technology
- Analog and Digital CMOS Design

